Cointegration Analysis relies on Engle-Granger Procedure (for pairs) or Johansen Procedure (for multivariate situations and general scanning).

While developing the strategy we rely on the frameworks of Vector Autoregression (Multivariate Linear Regression) and Cointegration Analysis (Vector Error Correction Model).

There are also tools: AIC/BIC for optimal lag selection, Dickey-Fuller Test for stationarity ("unit root"), Engle-Granger procedure for making cointegration between a pair explcit, and OU process for evaluating the quality of mean-reversion.


  • Vector Autoregression -- matrix form compupation. VAR is traditionally used on time series of Returns, however forecasting errors, such as MAPE will be $O(200\%)$ [FP Workshop I]

  • Vector Autoregression quick example (Ford, GM, SP500)


  • Engle-Granger Procedure to be implemented in full for each pair (2-3 pairs, more if interested) [Cointegration Lecture] [This Webex]
  • Fitting to OU process [This Webex]

Vector Auto Regression¶

This is a model-free set up in which we regress ''everything on everything". If asset returns are used -- they are made dependent on their own lagged values (past values). The system is endogenous.

You might also heard about dynamic structural equations modelling (DSEM). Well, Vector Autoregression is case of DSEM when there are no latent variables (all variables observable) and we rely on residuals. $p$ is the number of lagged values as determined by AIC, BIC tests.


\begin{eqnarray*} y_t &=& B_{\text{Constant}} + y_{t-1}B_1 + \cdots + y_{t-p}B_p +\varepsilon_t, \end{eqnarray*}

The following function VAR(data, p) estimates using Vector Autoregression in matrix form, calling on general multivariate linear regression model.

The function also checks stability of the system: whether all roots of the characteristic polynomials $\det(\lambda I - \widehat{B}_j)$ are within the unit circle for all $j = 1, \ldots, p$. If not, a warning will be issued.

The result is the estimated block matrix:

\begin{equation*} \widehat{B} = \left[ \begin{array}{l} \widehat{B}_{\text{Constant}} \\ \widehat{B}_1 \\ \vdots \\ \widehat{B}_p \\ \end{array} \right]. \end{equation*}

Multivariate Linear Regression¶

Consider a multivariate linear regression model in which we have $i=1, \ldots, m$ observations $y_i = (y_{i1}, \ldots, y_{in})^T$ that we are regressing on $x_i = (x_{i1}, \ldots, x_{i\ell})^T$:

\begin{equation*} \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} y_{11} & \cdots & y_{1n} \\ \vdots & & \vdots \\ y_{m1} & \cdots & y_{mn} \\ \end{array} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} x_{11} & \cdots & x_{1\ell} \\ \vdots & & \vdots \\ x_{m1} & \cdots & x_{m\ell} \\ \end{array} \right] \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} \beta_{11} & \cdots & \beta_{1n} \\ \vdots & & \vdots \\ \beta_{\ell1} & \cdots & \beta_{\ell n} \\ \end{array} \right] + \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} \varepsilon_{11} & \cdots & \varepsilon_{1n} \\ \vdots & & \vdots \\ \varepsilon_{m1} & \cdots & \varepsilon_{mn} \\ \end{array} \right] \end{equation*}


This forms the basis for both, Vector Autoregression and Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) Test. The model may also be written in short form as:

\begin{equation*} y_t = x_tB+\varepsilon_t, \end{equation*}

where $\varepsilon_t = (\varepsilon_{t1}, \ldots, \varepsilon_{tn})^T$ and we have substituted $t$ for $i$. In matrix notation the model may actually be written even shorter as:

\begin{equation*} Y = XB+\varepsilon \end{equation*}

linear_regression_core() computes regression coefficients (estimates the model), given pre-formed matricies.

\begin{equation*} \begin{array}{lcrcl} \text{Number of observations:} & \qquad & m & & \\ \text{Number of regressands:} & \qquad & n & & \\ \text{Number of regressors:} & \qquad & \ell & & \\ \text{Estimate of $B$:} & \qquad & \widehat{B} & = & (X^TX)^{-1}X^TY \\ \text{Residuals:} & \qquad & \widehat{\varepsilon}&= &Y-X\widehat{B} \\ \end{array} \end{equation*}

The following output is useful for inference: decisions on specification of regression model and significance of coeffiecients hypothesis testing (if the true value of coeffient is zero, we infer that corresponding variable does not have explanatory power).

\begin{equation*} \begin{array}{lcrcl} \text{Residual covariance matrix:} & \qquad & \widehat{\Sigma} &=& \widehat{\varepsilon}^T \widehat{\varepsilon} \big/ m\\ \text{Covariance matrix of regression coefficients:} & \qquad & \widehat{CoV} &=& \widehat{\Sigma}\otimes (X^TX)^{-1} \\ \text{Standard error of regression coefficient:} & \qquad & \left(\text{Var}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{kj}\right)\right)^{1/2}&=& \left(\frac{m}{m-\ell}\text{diag}(\widehat{CoV})_{kj}\right)^{1/2} \\ \text{t-test statistic for whether regression coefficient is zero:} & \qquad & \text{tstat}_{kj} &=& \widehat{\beta}_{kj}\big/\left(\text{Var}\left(\widehat{\beta}_{kj}\right)\right)^{1/2} \\ \text{$p$-value for the corresponding t-test statistic:} & \qquad & \text{pvalue}_{kj}&\\ \text{Akaike information criterion:} & \qquad & AIC & = & \log\left|\widehat{\Sigma}\right|+2\ell n\big/m \\ \text{Bayesian information criterion:} & \qquad & BIC & = & \log\left|\widehat{\Sigma}\right|+\log(m)\ell n\big/m \end{array} \end{equation*}
In [50]:
#PLEASE NOTE implement computation of various regression inference. Code omitted from release.

Cointegration modelling adds the constant (drift) and time-dependent variable (trend) to cointegrated relationship (cointegrated residual equation). It is the drift because $y_t$ participates in correction equation $\Delta y_t$.

The above general multivariate linear regression model is extended to:

\begin{eqnarray*} y_t &=& B_{\text{Constant}} + x_tB+\varepsilon_t,\quad\text{and}\\ y_t &=& B_{\text{Constant}} + tB_{\text{Trend}} + x_tB+\varepsilon_t. \end{eqnarray*}


Implemented simply by adding a line (or column) to dependent matrix $X$!

\begin{eqnarray*} X &=& \left[ \begin{array}{c|ccc} 1 & x_{11} & \cdots & x_{1\ell} \\ \vdots &\vdots & & \vdots \\ 1&x_{m1} & \cdots & x_{m\ell} \\ \end{array} \right],\quad\text{and}\\ X &=& \left[ \begin{array}{cc|ccc} 1 & 1 & x_{11} & \cdots & x_{1\ell} \\ \vdots &\vdots &\vdots & & \vdots \\ 1 & m &x_{m1} & \cdots & x_{m\ell} \\ \end{array} \right], \end{eqnarray*}

Cointegration Analysis¶

The idea is that a linear combination of two non-stationary time series (say, each is Brownian Motion) results in the residual, which is not stationary. That is not guaranteed. More formally, we say that Prices are I(1) time series (nonstaionary), whereas their combination -- a residual from naive regression is I(0) time series, or stationary.

In this section we implement the Engle-Granger procedure to confirm (or not) if the pair is cointegrated and therefore, suitable for trade design.

We begin by recapping what the prices for Ford and General Motors from before look like:


Engle-Granger Procedure¶

ENGLE-GRANGER STEP 1. ADF on Cointegrated Residual (spread e_t)¶

We are now ready to perform the 1st step of the Engle-Granger procedure which is to estimate the model:

\begin{equation} \text{Ford}_t = \beta \, \text{GM}_t + \mu_e + \varepsilon_t \end{equation}

and so, our NAIVE cointegrated residual is

\begin{equation} e_t = Ford_t - 0.4066 \, GM_t - 0.8682 \end{equation}

Vector cointegrating weights can be fine-tuned by running the ready multivariate cointegration (VECM routines, such as cajorls in R package urca )

\begin{equation} \boldsymbol\beta_{Coint} = [1, -0.4066] \qquad \qquad \mu_e = -0.8682 \end{equation}

The question now is whether the residual series is stationary -- has no unit root (randomness). We perform Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test on this Cointegrated residual (therefore, referred to as CADF).

NAIVE COINTEGRATING RELATIONSHIP Though the stationarity of residual is important, here it only transpires over > 4-year period. Regressing one equity price on another arbitrarily does not create cointegration. This is a first step in the analysis of a potential long-run relationship between the two time series $P^A_t$ and $P^B_t$.

ADF TEST EQUATION¶

\begin{equation*} \Delta e_t = \varphi e_{t-1} + \varphi_{aug1} \Delta e_{t-1} + const + \varphi_t t + \varepsilon_t \end{equation*}

Look at the value of test statistic for the parameter $\varphi$. In this case, it is -3.65 which is lower than the 5% Dickey-Fuller critical value of -3.45 (but not much lower). We reject the $H_0$ hypothesis of unit root (see Cointegration Lecture). The residuals are stationary.

  • Improvement 1. Test equation above includes time dependence $\varphi_t t$, referred to as 'trend'. DO NOT INCLUDE trend in your ADF tests and cointegrating residual -- it will make you think cointegration is present when it is very weak. In fact, without $\varphi_t t$ term, we might not even get stationarity result.
  • Improvement 2. To fully complete checks, we should estimate EG STEP 1 the other way around: General Motors on Ford. ADF on the residual form that regression gives stronger test statistic $-3.94$ for the parameter $\varphi$. We should have estimated model that way, but for now we proceed with Ford on GM way.

ENGLE-GRANGER STEP 2.¶

We are now in position to perform the 2nd step of Engle-Granger procedure which is to estimate the Equilibrium Correction Model, or error correction equations:

\begin{equation*} \Delta P^A_t = \varphi \Delta P^B_t - (1-\alpha) \widehat{e}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t \end{equation*}\begin{equation*} \Delta \text{Ford_Price}_t = \varphi \Delta\text{GM_Price}_t - (1-\alpha) \text{CointResidual_FordonGM}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t \end{equation*}\begin{equation*} \Delta \text{GM_Price}_t = \varphi \Delta\text{Ford_Price}_t - (1-\alpha) \text{CointResidual_GMonFord}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t \end{equation*}

  • Improvement 3. To reiterate, it would be a good practice to check the other way around: General Motors on Ford. Hence, this correction equation remains to be evaluated:
\begin{equation*} \Delta \text{GM_Price}_t = \varphi \Delta\text{Ford_Price}_t - (1-\alpha) \text{CointResidual_GMonFord}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t \end{equation*}

Once we established stationary cointegrated residual, that is statistically significantly affects correction in the Price at the next time step (notice that residual is $_{t-1}$) -- then we can proceed with the pairs trading strategy. Remember, we operate

\begin{equation} \boldsymbol\beta_{Coint} = [1, -0.4066] \qquad \qquad \mu_e = -0.8682 \end{equation}

ENGLE-GRANGER "STEP 3" Quality of Mean-Reversion¶

The strategy trades the spread from the long/short portfolio -- weights given $\boldsymbol\beta_{Coint}$. Profitability and trade-offs (frequency of trades vs. profit per trade) will become clearer from after we fit the cointegrated residual, spread $e_t$, to the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.

\begin{equation*} \text{d} e_{t+\tau} = -\theta(e_{t}-\mu) \,\text{dt}+\sigma_{OU} \text{dW}_t \end{equation*}


The fitting is guaranteed by AR(1) on the spread itself -- see Learning and Trusting Cointegration in Statistical Arbitrage by Richard Diamond, WILMOTT Magazine, November 2013, Issue 68. SSRN link

\begin{equation*} \widehat{e}_t = C + B \widehat{e}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t \end{equation*}

As mentioned earlier we could also have done the regression in step 1 the other way around, and we saw that the resulting residuals were also stationary. Had we done the entire Engle-Granger procedure the other way around, the resulting half-life would have been 28.4 days. Since this is similar to the above, we will stick with 'Ford' as being our lead variable.
